<link href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=193&amp;p=853#p853"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Is there an option to NOT remember folders view settings]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=193&amp;p=853#p853"><![CDATA[
If I'm working with files for example, I'd prefer to use detailed view. However, if I'm working with pictures or folders that might have pictures in it, I'd prefer to stick with Thumbnails. I did a bit more research and I think the term I'm referring to is &quot;Remember Each Folders View Settings&quot;. This was an option in Windows XP that you could 'uncheck' and then whatever view mode you're using at that moment, it would be no matter what folder you go into. I guess I was hoping that Classic Shell might have a similar option so if I open Windows Explorer, I could switch to detailed view and it would stay that way no matter what folder I pop into. Alternatively I could do the same with thumbnail view instead of it switching back and forth automatically depending on what <em>it thinks</em> I want.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=257">vgpclife</a> — Mon Feb 04, 2013 7:03 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
</entry>
